\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Ice Sheet: }{\fs20\cf0 The ground is covered with slippery ice. It costs 2 squares of movement to ent
er a square covered by an ice sheet, and the DC of Balance and Tumble checks there increases by 5. A DC 10 Balance check is required to run or charge across an ice sheet. 
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Light Rubble:}{\fs20\cf0  Small rocks are strewn across the ground, making nimble movement more difficult more difficult. The DC of Balance and Tumble checks increases by 2. 
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Dense Rubble:}{\fs20\cf0  This terrain feature consists of more and larger stones. It costs 2 squares of movement to enter a square with dense rubble. The DC of Balance and Tumble checks in
creases by 5, and the DC of Move Silently checks increases by 2.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Sand Dunes:}{\fs20\cf0  Created by the action of wind on sand, sand dunes function as hills that move. If the wind is strong and consistent, a sand dune can move several hundred feet in a week\rquote s time. Sa
nd dunes can cover hundreds of squares. They always have a gentle slope pointing in the direction of the prevailing wind and a steep slope on the leeward side.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Other Desert Terrain Features:}{\fs20\cf0  Tundra is sometimes bordered by forests, and the occasional tree isn\rquote 
t out of place in the cold wastes. Rocky deserts have towers and mesas consisting of flat ground surrounded on all sides by cliffs and steep slopes (described in Mountain Terrain, above). Sandy deserts sometimes have quicksand; this functions as descri
bed in Marsh Terrain, above, although desert quicksand is a waterless mixture of fine sand and dust. All desert terrain is crisscrossed with dry streambeds (treat as trenches 5 to 15 feet wide) that fill with water on the rare occasions when rain falls.

\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Stealth and Detection in the Desert:}{\fs20\cf0  In general, the maximum distance in desert terrain at which a Spot check for detecting the nearby presence of others can succeed is 6d6\'d7
20 feet; beyond this distance, elevation changes and heat distortion in warm deserts makes spotting impossible. The presence of dunes in sandy deserts limits spotting distance to 6d6\'d710 feet. 
\par The desert imposes neither bonuses nor penalties on Listen or Spot checks. The scarcity of undergrowth or other elements that offer concealment or cover makes hiding more difficult.
