\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20\cf0 
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Catapult, Heavy: }{\fs20\cf0 
A heavy catapult is a massive engine capable of throwing rocks or heavy objects with great force. Because the catapult throws its payload in a high arc, it can hit squares out of its line of sight. To fire a heavy catapult, the crew chief 
makes a special check against DC 15 using only his base attack bonus, Intelligence modifier, range increment penalty, and the appropriate modifiers from the lower section of Table 3\endash 
26. If the check succeeds, the catapult stone hits the square the catapult
 was aimed at, dealing the indicated damage to any object or character in the square. Characters who succeed on a DC 15 Reflex save take half damage. Once a catapult stone hits a square, subsequent shots hit the same square unless the catapult is reaimed 
or the wind changes direction or speed.
\par If a catapult stone misses, roll 1d8 to determine where it lands. This determines the misdirection of the throw, with 1 being back toward the catapult and 2 through 8 counting clockwise around the target square. Then,
 count 3 squares away from the target square for every range increment of the attack.
\par Loading a catapult requires a series of full-round actions. It takes a DC 15 Strength check to winch the throwing arm down; most catapults have wheels to allow up to two 
crew members to use the aid another action, assisting the main winch operator. A DC 15 Profession (siege engineer) check latches the arm into place, and then another DC 15 Profession (siege engineer) check loads the catapult ammunition. It takes four full
-round actions to reaim a heavy catapult (multiple crew members can perform these full-round actions in the same round, so it would take a crew of four only 1 round to reaim the catapult).
\par A heavy catapult takes up a space 15 feet across.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Catapult, Light: }{\fs20\cf0 T
his is a smaller, lighter version of the heavy catapult. It functions as the heavy catapult, except that it takes a DC 10 Strength check to winch the arm into place, and only two full-round actions are required to reaim the catapult.
\par A light catapult takes up a space 10 feet across.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Ballista:}{\fs20\cf0  A ballista is essentially a Huge heavy crossbow fixed in place. Its size makes it hard for most creatures to aim it}{\i\fs20\cf0 . }{\fs20\cf0 Thus, a Medium creature takes a \endash 
4 penalty on attack rolls when using a ballista, and a Small creature takes a \endash 6 penalty. It takes a creature smaller than Large two full-round actions to reload the ballista after firing.
\par A ballista takes up a space 5 feet across.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Ram: }{\fs20\cf0 This heavy pole is sometimes suspended from a movable scaffold that allows the crew to 
swing it back and forth against objects. As a full-round action, the character closest to the front of the ram makes an attack roll against the AC of the construction, applying the \endash 4 penalty for lack of proficiency. (It\rquote 
s not possible to be proficient with this device.) In addition to the damage given on Table: Siege Engines, up to nine other characters holding the ram can add their Strength modifier to the ram\rquote 
s damage, if they devote an attack action to doing so. It takes at least one Huge or larger creature, two Large creatures, four Medium-size creatures, or eight Small creatures to swing a ram. (Tiny or smaller creatures can\rquote t use a ram.)
\par A ram is typically 30 feet long. In a battle, the creatures wielding the ram stand in two adjacent columns of equal length, with the ram between them.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Siege Tower: }{\fs20\cf0 This device is a massive wooden tower on wheels or rollers that can be rolled up against a wall to allow attackers to scale the tower and thus to get to the top of the wall with cover. The wooden walls are u
sually 1 foot thick.
\par A typical siege tower takes up a space 15 feet across. The creatures inside push it at a speed of 10 feet (and a siege tower can\rquote t run). The eight creatures pushing on the ground floor have total cover, and those on higher floors get i
mproved cover and can fire through arrow slits.
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs21\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par City Streets
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 Typical city streets are narrow and twisting. Most streets average 15 to 20 feet wide [(1d4+1)\'d7
5 feet)], while alleys range from 10 feet wide to only 5 feet. Cobblestones in good condition allow normal movement, but ones in poor repair and heavily rutted dirt streets are considered light rubble, increasing the DC of Balance and Tumble checks by 2.

\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f2\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0 
Some cities have no larger thoroughfares, particularly cities that gradually grew from small settlements to larger cities. Cities that are planned, or perhaps have suffered a major fire that allowed authorities to construct new roads through formerly inha
bited areas, might have a few larger streets through town. These main roads are 25 feet wide\emdash offering room for wagons to pass each other\emdash with 5-foot-wide sidewalks on either side.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\fs20\cf0 Crowds: }{\fs20\cf0 Urban streets are often full of people going about their daily lives. In most cases, it isn\rquote 
t necessary to put every 1st-level commoner on the map when a fight breaks out on the city\rquote s main thoroughfare. Instead just indicate which squares on the map contain crowds. If crowds see something obviously dangerous, they\rquote ll move 
away at 30 feet per round at initiative count 0. It takes 2 squares of movement to enter a square with crowds. The crowds provide cover for anyone who does so, enabling a Hide check and providing a bonus to Armor Class and on Reflex saves.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Directing Crowds: }{\fs20\cf0 
It takes a DC 15 Diplomacy check or DC 20 Intimidate check to convince a crowd to move in a particular direction, and the crowd must be able to hear or see the character making the attempt. It takes a full-round action to make the Diplomacy check, but on
ly a free action to make the Intimidate check.
\par If two or more characters are trying to direct a crowd in different directions, they make opposed Diplomacy or Intimidate checks to determine whom the crowd listens to. The crowd ignores everyone if none of the characters\rquote 
 check results beat the DCs given above.
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs21\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par Above and beneath the Streets
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\fs20\cf0 Rooftops: }{\fs20\cf0 
Getting to a roof usually requires climbing a wall (see the Walls section), unless the character can reach a roof by jumping down from a higher window, balcony, 
or bridge. Flat roofs, common only in warm climates (accumulated snow can cause a flat roof to collapse), are easy to run across. Moving along the peak of a roof requires a DC 20 Balance check. Moving on an angled roof surface without changing altitude (m
oving parallel to the peak, in other words) requires a DC 15 Balance check. Moving up and down across the peak of a roof requires a DC 10 Balance check.
\par Eventually a character runs out of roof, requiring a long jump across to the next roof or down to the ground. The distance to the next closest roof is usually 1d3\'d7
5 feet horizontally, but the roof across the gap is equally likely to be 5 feet higher, 5 feet lower, or the same height. Use the guidelines in the Jump skill}{\i\fs20\cf0  }{\fs20\cf0 (a horizontal jump\rquote s peak height is on
e-fourth of the horizontal distance) to determine whether a character can make a jump.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Sewers:}{\fs20\cf0  To get into the sewers, most characters open a grate (a full-round action) and jump down 10 feet. Sewers are built exactly like dungeons, except that they\rquote re muc
h more likely to have floors that are slippery or covered with water. Sewers are also similar to dungeons in terms of creatures liable to be encountered therein. Some cities were built atop the ruins of older civilizations, so their sewers sometimes lead 
to treasures and dangers from a bygone age.
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs21\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
