\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 
Most city buildings fall into three categories. The majority of buildings in the city are two to five stories high, built side by side to form long rows separated by secondary or main streets. Thes
e row houses usually have businesses on the ground floor, with offices or apartments above.
\par Inns, successful businesses, and large warehouses\emdash as well as millers, tanners, and other businesses that require extra space\emdash  are generally large, free-standing buildings with up to five stories. 
\par Finally, small residences, shops, warehouses, or storage sheds are simple, one-story wooden buildings, especially if they\rquote re in poorer neighborhoods.
\par Most city buildings are made of a combination of stone or clay brick (on 
the lower one or two stories) and timbers (for the upper stories, interior walls, and floors). Roofs are a mixture of boards, thatch, and slates, sealed with pitch. A typical lower-story wall is 1 foot thick, with AC 3, hardness 8, 90 hp, and a Climb DC o
f 25. Upper-story walls are 6 inches thick, with AC 3, hardness 5, 60 hp, and a Climb DC of 21. Exterior doors on most buildings are good wooden doors that are usually kept locked, except on public buildings such as shops and taverns.
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs21\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
