\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 Bad weather frequently slows or halts travel and makes it virtually impossible to navigate from one spot to another
. Torrential downpours and blizzards obscure vision as effectively as a dense fog.
\par Most precipitation is rain, but in cold conditions it can manifest as snow, sleet, or hail. Precipitation of any kind followed by a cold snap in which the temperature dips from above freezing to 30\'b0 F or below may produce ice. }{\i\fs20\cf0 Rain: }{
\fs20\cf0 Rain reduces visibility ranges by half, resulting in a \endash 4 penalty on Spot and Search checks. It has the same effect on flames, ranged weapon attacks, and Listen checks as severe wind.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Snow: }{\fs20\cf0 Falling snow has the same effects on visibility, ranged weapon attacks, and skill checks as rain, and it costs 2 squares of movement to enter a snow-covered square. A day of snowfall leaves 1d6 inches of snow on the ground.

\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Heavy Snow: }{\fs20\cf0 Heavy snow has the same ef
fects as normal snowfall, but also restricts visibility as fog does (see Fog, below). A day of heavy snow leaves 1d4 feet of snow on the ground, and it costs 4 squares of movement to enter a square covered with heavy snow. Heavy snow accompanied by strong
 or severe winds may result in snowdrifts 1d4\'d75 feet deep, especially in and around objects big enough to deflect the wind\emdash 
a cabin or a large tent, for instance. There is a 10% chance that a heavy snowfall is accompanied by lightning (see Thunderstorm, below). Snow has the same effect on flames as moderate wind.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Sleet: }{\fs20\cf0 Essentially frozen rain, sleet has the same effect as rain while falling (except that its chance to extinguish protected flames is 75%) and the same effect as snow once on the ground. 
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Hail: }{\fs20\cf0 Hail does not reduce visibility, but the sound of falling hail makes Listen checks more difficult (\endash 
4 penalty). Sometimes (5% chance) hail can become large enough to deal 1 point of lethal damage (per storm) to anything in the open. Once on the ground, hail has the same effect on movement as snow.
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs21\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Storms
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 
The combined effects of precipitation (or dust) and wind that accompany all storms reduce visibility ranges by three quarters, imposing a \endash 8 penalty on Spot, Search, and Listen checks. Storms make ranged we
apon attacks impossible, except for those using siege weapons, which have a \endash 
4 penalty on attack rolls. They automatically extinguish candles, torches, and similar unprotected flames. They cause protected flames, such as those of lanterns, to dance wildly 
and have a 50% chance to extinguish these lights. See Table: Wind Effects for possible consequences to creatures caught outside without shelter during such a storm. Storms are divided into the following three types. 
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Duststorm (CR 3): }{\fs20\cf0 These desert storms d
iffer from other storms in that they have no precipitation. Instead, a duststorm blows fine grains of sand that obscure vision, smother unprotected flames, and can even choke protected flames (50% chance). Most duststorms are accompanied by severe winds a
n
d leave behind a deposit of 1d6 inches of sand. However, there is a 10% chance for a greater duststorm to be accompanied by windstorm-magnitude winds (see Table: Wind Effects). These greater duststorms deal 1d3 points of nonlethal damage each round to any
one caught out in the open without shelter and also pose a choking hazard (see Drowning\emdash except that a character with a scarf or similar protection across her mouth and nose does not begin to choke until after a number of rounds equal to 10 \'d7
 her Constitution score). Greater duststorms leave 2d3\endash 1 feet of fine sand in their wake.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Snowstorm: }{\fs20\cf0 In addition to the wind and precipitation common to other storms, snowstorms leave 1d6 inches of snow on the ground afterward. 
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Thunderstorm: }{\fs20\cf0 In addition to wind and preci
pitation (usually rain, but sometimes also hail), thunderstorms are accompanied by lightning that can pose a hazard to characters without proper shelter (especially those in metal armor). As a rule of thumb, assume one bolt per minute for a 1-hour period 
at the center of the storm. Each bolt causes electricity damage equal to 1d10 eight-sided dice. One in ten thunderstorms is accompanied by a tornado (see below). 
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Powerful Storms:}{\fs20\cf0  Very high winds and torrential precipitation reduce visibility to zero, makin
g Spot, Search, and Listen checks and all ranged weapon attacks impossible. Unprotected flames are automatically extinguished, and protected flames have a 75% chance of being doused. Creatures caught in the area must make a DC 20 Fortitude save or face th
e effects based on the size of the creature (see Table: Wind Effects). Powerful storms are divided into the
\par following four types.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Windstorm: }{\fs20\cf0 While accompanied by little or no precipitation, windstorms can cause considerable damage simply through the force of their wind.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Blizzard: }{\fs20\cf0 The combination of high winds, heavy snow (typically 1d3 feet), and bitter cold make blizzards deadly for all who are unprepared for them.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Hurricane: }{\fs20\cf0 In addition to very high winds and heavy rain, hurricanes are accompanied by floods. Most adventuring activity is impossible under such conditions.
