\par HEAT DANGERS
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Heat deals nonlethal damage that cannot be recovered until the character gets cooled off (reaches shade, survives until nightfall, gets doused in water, is targeted by }{\i\fs20\cf0 endure elements}{\fs20\cf0 
, and so forth). Once rendered unconscious through the accumulation of nonlethal damage, the character begins to take lethal damage at the same rate.
\par A character in very hot conditions (above 90\'b0 F) must make a Fortitude saving throw each hour (DC 15, +1 for each previous check) or take 1d4 points of nonlethal damage. Characters wearing heavy clothing or armor of any sort take a \endash 
4 penalty on their saves. A character with the Survival skill may receive
 a bonus on this saving throw and may be able to apply this bonus to other characters as well (see the skill description). Characters reduced to unconsciousness begin taking lethal damage (1d4 points per hour).
\par In severe heat (above 110\'b0 F), a character must make a Fortitude save once every 10 minutes (DC 15, +1 for each previous check) or take 1d4 points of nonlethal damage. Characters wearing heavy clothing or armor of any sort take a \endash 
4 penalty on their saves. A character with the Survival skill may rece
ive a bonus on this saving throw and may be able to apply this bonus to other characters as well. Characters reduced to unconsciousness begin taking lethal damage (1d4 points per each 10-minute period).
\par A character who takes any nonlethal damage from heat exposure now suffers from heatstroke and is fatigued.
\par These penalties end when the character recovers the nonlethal damage she took from the heat.
\par Extreme heat (air temperature over 140\'b0 F, fire, boiling water, lava) deals lethal damage. Breathing air in t
hese temperatures deals 1d6 points of damage per minute (no save). In addition, a character must make a Fortitude save every 5 minutes (DC 15, +1 per previous check) or take 1d4 points of nonlethal damage. Those wearing heavy clothing or any sort of armor
 take a \endash 4 penalty on their saves. In addition, those wearing metal armor or coming into contact with very hot metal are affected as if by a }{\i\fs20\cf0 heat metal }{\fs20\cf0 spell.
\par Boiling water deals 1d6 points of scalding damage, unless the character is fully immersed, in which case it deals 10d6 points of damage per round of exposure.
